{"parse":{"title":"CIOMS/RUCAM scale","pageid":17363295,"revid":819696957,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>CIOMS/RUCAM scale</b> is a tool to predict whether <a href=\"/wiki/Liver\" title=\"Liver\">liver</a> damage can be attributed to a particular <a href=\"/wiki/Medication\" title=\"Medication\">medication</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Hepatotoxicity\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Hepatotoxicity</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Interpretation\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Interpretation</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Hepatotoxicity\">Hepatotoxicity</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=CIOMS/RUCAM_scale&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Hepatotoxicity\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Determining <a href=\"/wiki/Hepatotoxicity\" title=\"Hepatotoxicity\">hepatotoxicity</a> (toxic effects of a substance on the liver) remains a major challenge in clinical practice due to lack of reliable markers.<sup id=\"cite_ref-pmid17230599_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-pmid17230599-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Many other conditions lead to similar clinical as well as pathological picture. To diagnose hepatotoxicity, a causal relationship between the use of the toxin or drug and subsequent liver damage has to be established, but might be difficult, especially when idiosyncratic reaction is suspected.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Simultaneous use of multiple drugs may add to the complexity. As in <a href=\"/wiki/Acetaminophen\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Acetaminophen\">acetaminophen</a> toxicity, well established dose dependent pharmacological hepatotoxicity is easier to spot.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Interpretation\">Interpretation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=CIOMS/RUCAM_scale&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Interpretation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Council_for_International_Organizations_of_Medical_Sciences\" title=\"Council for International Organizations of Medical Sciences\">CIOMS</a>/RUCAM scale has been proposed to establish causal relationship between offending drug and liver damage. The CIOMS/RUCAM scale involves a scoring system which categorizes the suspicion into \"definite or highly probable\" (score &gt; 8), \"probable\" (score 6-8), \"possible\" (score 3-5), \"unlikely\" (score 1-2) and \"excluded\" (score \u2264 0). In clinical practice physicians put more emphasis on the presence or absence of similarity between the biochemical profile of the patient and known biochemical profile of the suspected toxicity ( e.g. cholestatic damage in <a href=\"/wiki/Co-amoxiclav\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Co-amoxiclav\">amoxycillin-clauvonic acid</a> ).<sup id=\"cite_ref-pmid17230599_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-pmid17230599-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=CIOMS/RUCAM_scale&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-pmid17230599-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-pmid17230599_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-pmid17230599_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Andrade RJ, Robles M, Fern\u00e1ndez-Casta\u00f1er A, L\u00f3pez-Ortega S, L\u00f3pez-Vega MC, Lucena MI (2007). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.wjgnet.com/1007-9327/13/329.asp\">\"Assessment of drug-induced hepatotoxicity in clinical practice: a challenge for gastroenterologists\"</a>. <i>World J. Gastroenterol</i>. <b>13</b> (3): 329\u201340. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.3748/wjg.v13.i3.329\">10.3748/wjg.v13.i3.329</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17230599\">17230599</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=World+J.+Gastroenterol.&amp;rft.atitle=Assessment+of+drug-induced+hepatotoxicity+in+clinical+practice%3A+a+challenge+for+gastroenterologists&amp;rft.volume=13&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=329-40&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.3748%2Fwjg.v13.i3.329&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F17230599&amp;rft.aulast=Andrade&amp;rft.aufirst=R